4. Technical Architecture: Offline-First & Data Integrity

Given the connectivity challenges in Malakal PoC, the attendance module utilizes a PWA framework with an offline-first architecture. All data entry is written immediately to IndexedDB and queued for manual sync.

Conflict Resolution: The system employs a "last-write-wins" protocol based on client-side timestamps. However, for duplicate session metadata, the server will return an HTTP 409 Conflict response, triggering a manual resolution prompt for the user to "Add to" or "Replace" the existing record.

Data Integrity: Version 4 UUIDs are generated client-side at the point of save to prevent ID collisions during bulk syncs.

Required IndexedDB Stores:

[ ] beneficiaries: Cached list of all children in the user's assigned sector.

[ ] cfs_registrations: Links children to specific CFS locations.

[ ] cfs_sessions: Stores the metadata for each session (date, type, facilitator).

[ ] attendance_records: Individual presence/absence logs for each child.

[ ] case_identification_flags: Stores protection flags raised during sessions.

5. Database Schema & TRD Additions

To support multiple activities per day at a single location, the cfs_sessions table includes session categorization. This is critical for supporting the three V1 types: general_group_activity, teamup, and children_sessions.

-- Schema Modification for US-CFS-ATT-001
ALTER TABLE cfs_sessions
ADD COLUMN session_type VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL;

ALTER TABLE cfs_sessions
ADD CONSTRAINT session_type_check
CHECK (session_type IN ('general_group_activity', 'teamup', 'children_sessions'));

-- Update unique constraint to allow multiple types per day
ALTER TABLE cfs_sessions
DROP CONSTRAINT cfs_sessions_unique_loc_date;

ALTER TABLE cfs_sessions
ADD CONSTRAINT cfs_sessions_unique_loc_date_type
UNIQUE (cfs_location_id, session_date, session_type);


Unique Constraint Rationale: The transition from a (location, date) constraint to a (location, date, session_type) constraint allows a facilitator to record a "TeamUp" session in the morning and a "Children Session" in the afternoon at the same site without database conflicts.

